column11: The historic Colombia-FARC peace agreement stipulated that the FARC could register as a political party once disarmament was complete (United Press International, Colombia Reports 1/10/2017 , Colombia Reports 6/8/2017 , Reuters). The FARC has said it is committed to forming a political party, a process which could involve Voices of Peace and Reconciliation or the establishment of a new organization (Telesur, Fox News). Confused? Check our FAQ or ask us for help.

column6: Leaders of the now-demobilized FARC guerrilla group went to the offices of Colombia's National Electoral Council (CNE) on Monday to register their new political party to participate in the 2018 elections.

I am sure: Founding a party does NOT equal registration, so the question will NOT resolve on 1 September if the FARC would have founded a party at that date (see for some information on registration the link, here: http://www.eltiempo.com/politica/partidos-politicos/partido-politico-de-las-farc-103928).

What does "register" mean? As far as I know about the terms in use concerning political parties, If they would found a party on 1st September this will NOT imply registration... Founding a party and registration are distinct processes for all that I have read about the founding of political parties around the world. There exist parties who were not officially registered: e.g. some extremist or populist parties... Registration is officially used term for the official recognition of a party by the administration!

The FARC may form a political party before the end of September, but the vitriol against them right now has similarities to the slaughter of the Union Patriotica, the FARC's first attempt at a political party in the 1980's. The demise of the UP is still remembered by Colombians, and should serve as a cautionary tale about the perils of rushing into the political arena, especially considering the UP and the FARC were significantly more popular than the FARC currently is.

The 58 yr old leader of Colombia's Farc rebel group, Rodrigo Londoño, (aka Timochenko), commander of FARC since 2011, is being treated in hospital for a stroke. He is expected to leave hospital on Tuesday and make a full recovery. He was admitted to hospital Sunday morning. His health is "in a stable and satisfactory condition," doctors said in a press conference. He suffered a heart attack two years ago when he was in Cuba negotiating a peace deal with Colombian officials.

I don't think this will affect the process significantly, but it might slow the FARC down, as they generally like to have consensus on major issues, at least among the Secretariat (http://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-40476101). However, given Timochenko is supportive of the peace process and appears to be in stable condition, it's likely the rest of the Secretariat will move forward as planned.

I'm not as optimistic as others that this is a sure thing before the end of September. While the FARC has made significant progress compared to the previous three peace processes, the road to peace and the eventual creation of a political party can be longer and more winding than we are accustomed to in the western democracies. To simply assume that the FARC has met its requirements and will be unanimously supported by the Colombian people and government in creating a peace process is to overlook the past 50 years. And while I understand that the Santos administration has committed itself to peace, let's not forget former President, now Congressman Uribe and his efforts to undermine the peace process in favor of complete elimination of the FARC through military force.

The FARC insurgency in Colombia has continued for more than six decades. Belief is a powerful force, and the FARC rebels have been willing to execute extreme measures for their beliefs. The unabbreviated English translation of the name of the group is the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia--People's Army. The symbolic turnover of arms and deadlines from the peace agreement seem to be baby steps. If I were in negotiations with FARC, the first thing I would ask is for a name change. Having the word armed in the formal name of a rebel group is a poor way to begin a pivot to a legitimate political party. I predict FARC will not have a registered political party for a long time.
